'''Bandwidth''' is a [[Platform as a service#Communications platform as a service (CPaaS)|Communications Platform as a Service (CPaaS)]] company.  They sell software application programming interfaces (or APIs) for voice and messaging, using their own IP voice network.

==History==
Formed in 1999, Bandwidth by co-founder David Morken and {{who|date=November 2018}}. Bandwidth moved to North Carolina in {{when|date=November 2018}} at the [[Centennial Campus of North Carolina State University]] in [[Raleigh, North Carolina]]. As of December 31, 2017, Bandwidth maintains a [[workforce]] of 378 [[employees]].<sup>[<nowiki/>[[Bandwidth (company)#cite%20note-4|4]]]</sup>{{verify source|date=November 2018}} Bandwidth reported Q2 2018 revenue of $48.3 million. {{citation needed|date=November 2018}}

In November 2017, the company had an [[initial public offering]] on the [[NASDAQ]].{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}

== Products & Services ==
Bandwidth offers communications APIs that allow companies to embed voice calling and messaging capability into their applications; [[Enhanced 9-1-1|enhanced 911]] (emergency) calling; and access to [[Virtual number|virtual phone numbers]].

==Partnership==
In July 2011, Bandwidth Inc. started working with Alabama's 911 (emergency) centers to allow people to send text messages, pictures and videos to 911.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.al.com/spotnews/2011/07/photos_texting_on_horizon_for.html|title=Photos, texting, videos on horizon for Alabama's future emergency 911 calls|last=Gray|first=Jeremy|date=July 18, 2011|publisher=The Birmingham News|accessdate=August 3, 2011}}</ref>

Bandwidth Inc. manages the assignment of telephone numbers for [[Google Voice]]— a carrier search on a Google Voice number, for example, will indicate that the carrier's identity is Bandwidth Inc.

